{"title_page": "Shaybanids", "text_new": "{{for|the Arab ruling house of Shirvan|Mazyadid dynasty}}\n[[Image:Shaybani ger.jpg|right|thumb|170px|The trellis-walled yurt of [[Muhammad Shaybani]] [[Khan (title)|Khan]].]]\nThe '''Shaybanids''' ({{lang-fa|\u0633\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0647 \u0634\u06cc\u0628\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646}}) were a [[Persianization|Persianized]]<ref name=\"Canfield19\">''Introduction: The Turko-Persian tradition'', Robert L. Canfield, '''Turko-Persia in Historical Perspective''', ed. Robert L. Canfield, (Cambridge University Press, 1999), 19.</ref>  [[Turko-Mongol]] dynasty<ref>[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/abul-khayrids-dynasty]</ref> in Central Asia.<ref>''Shibanids'', R.D. McChesney, '''The Encyclopaedia of Islam''', Vol. IX, ed. C. E. Bosworth, E. Van Donzel, W. P. Heinrichs AND G. Lecomte, (Brill, 1986), 428;\"''SHIBANIDS, a Mongol dynasty of Central Asia, the agnatic descendants of Shiban, the fifth son of Djoci son of Cinggis Khan''\".</ref> They were the patrilineal descendants of [[Shiban]], the fifth son of [[Jochi]] and grandson of [[Genghis Khan]].<ref name=\"Grousset478\">Rene Grousset, ''The Empire of the Steppes'', transl. Naomi Walford, (Rutgers University Press, 1970), 478.</ref> Until the mid-14th century, they acknowledged the authority of the descendants of Shiban's brothers [[Batu Khan]] and [[Orda Khan]], such as [[\u00d6z Beg Khan]]. The Shaybanids, originally led the grey horde southeast of the Urals (also known as the Uzbegs ([[Uzbeks]])), converted to [[Islam]] in 1282. At its height, the khanate included parts of modern-day [[Afghanistan]] and parts of [[central Asia]].\n\nAs the [[Descent from Genghis Khan|lineages of Batu and Orda]] died out in the course of the great civil wars of the 14th century, the Shaybanids under [[Abu'l-Khayr Khan]] declared themselves the only legitimate successors to Jochi and put forward claims to the whole of his enormous [[Ulus of Jochi|ulus]], which included parts of [[Siberia]] and [[Kazakhstan]]. Their rivals were the [[Timurid dynasty]], who claimed descent from Jochi's thirteenth son by a concubine. Several decades of strife left the Timurids in control of the [[Great Horde]] and its successor states in Europe, namely, the Khanates of [[Khanate of Kazan|Kazan]], [[Astrakhan Khanate|Astrakhan]], and [[Crimean Khanate|Crimea]].\n\n==Shaybanid dynasty==\n[[File:Shaybani.jpg|thumb|\n[[Muhammad Shaybani]].]]\n\nUnder [[Abu'l-Khayr Khan]] (who led the Shaybanids from 1428 to 1468), the dynasty began consolidating disparate Ozbeg (Uzbek) tribes, first in the area around [[Tyumen]] and the [[Tura River]] and then down into the [[Syr Darya]] region. His grandson [[Muhammad Shaybani]] (ruled 1500-10), who gave his name to the Shaybanid dynasty, conquered [[Samarkand]], [[Herat]],<ref name=\"Grousset478\" /> [[Balkh]]<ref name=\"Grousset478\" /> and [[Bukhara]],<ref name=\"Grousset478\" /> thus ending the Timurid dynasty and establishing the short-lived Shaybanid Empire.<ref>Svat Soucek, ''A History of Inner Asia'', (Cambridge University Press, 2000), 149.</ref> After his death at the hands of [[Shah Ismail I]], he was followed successively by an uncle, a cousin, and a brother, whose Shaybanid descendants would rule the [[Khanate of Bukhara]] from 1505 until 1598 and the [[Khanate of Khiva|Khanate of Khwarezm (Khiva)]] from 1511 until 1695.\n\nAnother state ruled by the Shaybanids was the [[Khanate of Sibir]], seizing the throne in 1563. Its last khan, [[Kuchum]], was [[Russian conquest of Siberia|deposed by the Russians]] in 1598. He escaped to [[Bukhara]], but his sons and grandsons were taken by the Tsar to [[Moscow]], where they eventually assumed the surname of [[Sibirsky (surname)|Sibirsky]]. Apart from this famous branch, several other noble families from [[Kyrgyzstan]] and [[Kazakhstan]] (e.g., Princes [[Valikhanov]]) petitioned the Russian imperial authorities to recognise their [[Shaybanid]] roots, but mostly in vain.\n\n==Khans of Shaybanid dynasty of [[Khanate of Bukhara]]==\n{| width=100% class=\"wikitable\" \n! style=\"background-color:#F0DC82\" width=27% | Titular Name\n! style=\"background-color:#F0DC82\" width=25% | Personal Name\n! style=\"background-color:#F0DC82\" width=25% | Reign \n|-\n|colspan=3 align=\"middle\"| They were the descendants of [[Shiban]], fifth son of [[Jochi]] ruling in Western [[Siberia]]. Later a major faction split and made a dash for [[Transoxiana]] and adopted the name [[Uzbeks|Uzbek]] (Ozbeg) after their famous ''Khan'', [[Uzbeg Khan]]. The faction that remained behind in Siberia created the [[Khanate of Sibir]] and lasted until the 16th century. \n|-\n|- style=\"background:lightblue\"\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small> <br>\n|align=\"center\"| '''[[Abu'l-Khayr Khan|Abul-Khayr Khan ibn Dawlat Shaykh ibn Ibrahim Khan]]''' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u06cc\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u062f\u0648\u0644\u062a \u0634\u06cc\u062e \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1428 - 1468 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small> <br>''Shaykh Hayder'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq|-}} </small> <br>\n|align=\"center\"| '''[[Shah Budagh Khan|Shah Budagh Khan ibn Abul-Khayr Khan]]'''<br> <small>{{Nastaliq|  \u0634\u0627\u0647 \u0628\u062f\u0627\u063a \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u06cc\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1468 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small> <br>''Abul-Fath'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u062a\u062d}} </small> <br>\n|align=\"center\"| '''[[Muhammad Shaybani|Muhammad Shayabak Khan ibn Shah Budagh Khan ibn Abul-Khayr Khan]]'''<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0627\u06cc\u0628\u06a9 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u06c1 \u0628\u062f\u0627\u063a \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u06cc\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1500 \u2013 1510 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|  ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"| [[Kochkunju Muhammad bin Abul-Khayr Khan]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u06a9\u0686\u06be\u06a9\u0646\u062c\u0648 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u06cc\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1512 \u2013 1531 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br> ''Muzaffar-al-Din'' <br><small>{{Nastaliq| \u0645\u0638\u0641\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u06cc\u0646}} </small> \n|align=\"center\"| [[Abu Sa'id bin Kochkunju]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0633\u0639\u06cc\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u06a9\u0686\u06be\u06a9\u0646\u062c\u0648 }} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1531 \u2013 1534 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|  ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br> ''Abul Ghazi'' <br><small>{{Nastaliq| \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u063a\u0627\u0632\u06cc}} </small> \n|align=\"center\"| [[Ubaydullah Sultan|Ubaydullah bin Mahmud bin Shah Budagh]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0639\u0628\u06cc\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u0647 \u0628\u062f\u0627\u063a}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1534 \u2013 1539 C.E. \n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br> \n|align=\"center\"| [[Abdullah Khan I|Abdullah bin Kochkunju]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0646 \u06a9\u0686\u06be\u06a9\u0646\u062c\u0648 }} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1539 \u2013 1540 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|  ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br>\n|align=\"center\"| [[Abdal-Latif bin Kochkunju]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0637\u06cc\u0641 \u0628\u0646 \u06a9\u0686\u06be\u06a9\u0646\u062c\u0648 }} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1540 \u2013 1552 C.E. \n|-\n|align=\"center\"|  ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br>\n|align=\"center\"| [[Nawruz Ahmed|Nawruz Ahmed bin Sunjuq bin Abul-Khayr Khan]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0646\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0632 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0633\u0646\u062c\u0642 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u06cc\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1552 \u2013 1556 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br>\n|align=\"center\"| [[Pir Muhammad Khan I|Pir Muhammad Khan bin Jani Beg]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u067e\u06cc\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u06cc\u06af}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1556 \u2013 1561 C.E. \n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br>\n|align=\"center\"| [[Iskander bin Jani Beg]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0627\u0633\u06a9\u0646\u062f\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u06cc\u06af}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1561 \u2013 1583 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|  ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br>''Buzurg Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0628\u0632\u0631\u06af \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br>''Abdullah Khan Uzbek'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0632\u0628\u06a9}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"| '''[[Abdullah Khan II|Abdullah Khan bin Iskander]]'''<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u06a9\u0646\u062f\u0631}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1583 \u2013 1598 C.E. \n|-\n|align=\"center\"|  ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br>\n|align=\"center\"| [[Abdul-Mo'min bin Abdullah Khan]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0645\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u062e\u0627\u0646 }} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1598 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|  ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small><br>\n|align=\"center\"| [[Pir Muhammad Khan II|Pir Muhammad Khan bin Sulayman Khan bin Jani Beg]]<br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u067e\u06cc\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0633\u0644\u06cc\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u062c\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u06cc\u06af}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1598 \u2013 1599 C.E. \n|-\n|colspan=3 align=\"middle\"| Khanate of Bukhara taken over by a new dynasty called the Janids also known as Toqay-Temurids (descendants of Khans of Astrakhan).\n|}\n**''Blue Row Signifies progenitor chief.''\n***''Khans of significance highlighted in Bold''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Vasily Bartold|Bartold, Vasily]] (1964) ''The Shaybanids''. Collected Works, vol. 2, part 2. Moscow, 1964.\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Grousset|Grousset, Ren\u00e9]] (1970) ''The Empire of the Steppes: a history of central Asia'' Rutgers University Press, New Brunswick, NJ, (translated by Naomi Walford from the French edition, published by Payot in 1970), pp.&nbsp;478\u2013490 ''et passim'', {{ISBN|0-8135-0627-1}}\n* [[Clifford Edmund Bosworth|Bosworth, C.E.]] (1996) ''The new Islamic dynasties: a chronological and genealogical manual'' Columbia University Press, New York, pp.&nbsp;288\u20139, {{ISBN|0-231-10714-5}}\n* Soucek, Svatopluk (2000) ''A History of Inner Asia'' Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, pp.&nbsp;149\u2013157, {{ISBN|0-521-65169-7}}\n* Erkinov A. \u201cThe Poetry of the Nomads and Shaybani Rulers of Transition to a Settled Society\u201d. In: Central Asia on Display: Proceedings of the VII. Conference of the European Society for Central Asian Studies (27\u201330 September 2000). G.Rasuly-Paleczek, J. Katsching (eds). Vienna, 2005. P.145-150.\n\n[[Category:Mongol khans]]\n[[Category:Mongol dynasties]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Uzbek people]]\n[[Category:Khanate of Bukhara]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Arab ruling house of Shirvan|Mazyadid dynasty}}\n[[Image:Shaybani ger.jpg|right|thumb|170px|The trellis-walled yurt of [[Muhammad Shaybani]] [[Khan (title)|Khan]].]]\nThe '''Shaybanids''' ({{lang-fa|\u0633\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0647 \u0634\u06cc\u0628\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646}}) were a [[Persianization|Persianized]]<ref name=\"Canfield19\">''Introduction: The Turko-Persian tradition'', Robert L. Canfield, '''Turko-Persia in Historical Perspective''', ed. Robert L. Canfield, (Cambridge University Press, 1999), 19.</ref>  [[Turko-Mongol]] dynasty<ref>[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/abul-khayrids-dynasty]</ref> in Central Asia.<ref>''Shibanids'', R.D. McChesney, '''The Encyclopaedia of Islam''', Vol. IX, ed. C. E. Bosworth, E. Van Donzel, W. P. Heinrichs AND G. Lecomte, (Brill, 1986), 428;\"''SHIBANIDS, a Mongol dynasty of Central Asia, the agnatic descendants of Shiban, the fifth son of Djoci son of Cinggis Khan''\".</ref> They were the patrilineal descendants of [[Shiban]], the fifth son of [[Jochi]] and grandson of [[Genghis Khan]].<ref name=\"Grousset478\">Rene Grousset, ''The Empire of the Steppes'', transl. Naomi Walford, (Rutgers University Press, 1970), 478.</ref> Until the mid-14th century, they acknowledged the authority of the descendants of Shiban's brothers [[Batu Khan]] and [[Orda Khan]], such as [[\u00d6z Beg Khan]]. The Shaybanids originally led the grey horde southeast of the Urals, also known as the Uzbegs ([[Uzbeks]]), was converted to [[Islam]] in 1282. At its height, the khanate included parts of modern-day [[Afghanistan]] and parts of [[central Asia]].\n\nAs the [[Descent from Genghis Khan|lineages of Batu and Orda]] died out in the course of the great civil wars of the 14th century, the Shaybanids under [[Abu'l-Khayr Khan]] declared themselves the only legitimate successors to Jochi and put forward claims to the whole of his enormous [[Ulus of Jochi|ulus]], which included parts of [[Siberia]] and [[Kazakhstan]]. Their rivals were the [[Timurid dynasty]], who claimed descent from Jochi's thirteenth son by a concubine. Several decades of strife left the Timurids in control of the [[Great Horde]] and its successor states in Europe, namely, the Khanates of [[Khanate of Kazan|Kazan]], [[Astrakhan Khanate|Astrakhan]], and [[Crimean Khanate|Crimea]].\n\n==Shaybanid dynasty==\n[[File:Shaybani.jpg|thumb|\n[[Muhammad Shaybani]].]]\n\nUnder [[Abu'l-Khayr Khan]] (who led the Shaybanids from 1428 to 1468), the dynasty began consolidating disparate Ozbeg (Uzbek) tribes, first in the area around [[Tyumen]] and the [[Tura River]] and then down into the [[Syr Darya]] region. His grandson [[Muhammad Shaybani]] (ruled 1500-10), who gave his name to the Shaybanid dynasty, conquered [[Samarkand]], [[Herat]],<ref name=\"Grousset478\" /> [[Balkh]]<ref name=\"Grousset478\" /> and [[Bukhara]],<ref name=\"Grousset478\" /> thus ending the Timurid dynasty and establishing the short-lived Shaybanid Empire.<ref>Svat Soucek, ''A History of Inner Asia'', (Cambridge University Press, 2000), 149.</ref> After his death at the hands of [[Shah Ismail I]], he was followed successively by an uncle, a cousin, and a brother, whose Shaybanid descendants would rule the [[Khanate of Bukhara]] from 1505 until 1598 and the [[Khanate of Khiva|Khanate of Khwarezm (Khiva)]] from 1511 until 1695.\n\nAnother state ruled by the Shaybanids was the [[Khanate of Sibir]], seizing the throne in 1563. Its last khan, [[Kuchum]], was [[Russian conquest of Siberia|deposed by the Russians]] in 1598. He escaped to [[Bukhara]], but his sons and grandsons were taken by the Tsar to [[Moscow]], where they eventually assumed the surname of [[Sibirsky (surname)|Sibirsky]]. Apart from this famous branch, several other noble families from [[Kyrgyzstan]] and [[Kazakhstan]] (e.g., Princes [[Valikhanov]]) petitioned the Russian imperial authorities to recognise their [[Shaybanid]] roots, but mostly in vain.\n\n==Khans of Shaybanid dynasty of [[Khanate of Bukhara]]==\n{| width=100% class=\"wikitable\" \n! style=\"background-color:#F0DC82\" width=27% | Titular Name\n! style=\"background-color:#F0DC82\" width=25% | Personal Name\n! style=\"background-color:#F0DC82\" width=25% | Reign \n|-\n|colspan=3 align=\"middle\"| They were the descendants of [[Shiban]], fifth son of [[Jochi]] ruling in Western [[Siberia]]. Later a major faction split and made a dash for [[Transoxiana]] and adopted the name [[Uzbeks|Uzbek]] (Ozbeg) after their famous ''Khan'', [[Uzbeg Khan]]. The faction that remained behind in Siberia created the [[Khanate of Sibir]] and lasted until the 16th century. \n|-\n|- style=\"background:lightblue\"\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small> <br>\n|align=\"center\"| '''[[Abu'l-Khayr Khan|Abul-Khayr Khan ibn Dawlat Shaykh ibn Ibrahim Khan]]''' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u06cc\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u062f\u0648\u0644\u062a \u0634\u06cc\u062e \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1428 - 1468 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small> <br>''Shaykh Hayder'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq|-}} </small> <br>\n|align=\"center\"| '''[[Shah Budagh Khan|Shah Budagh Khan ibn Abul-Khayr Khan]]'''<br> <small>{{Nastaliq|  \u0634\u0627\u0647 \u0628\u062f\u0627\u063a \u062e\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u06cc\u0631 \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small>\n|align=\"center\"|1468 C.E.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ''Khan'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u062e\u0627\u0646}} </small> <br>''Abul-Fath'' <br> <small>{{Nastaliq| \u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u062a\u062d}} </small> <br>